Pharmacology of the Autonomic Nervous System 

Wednesday, April 5, 2017 

8:23 AM 

Define muscarinic/nicotinic and adrenergic/cholinergic.  

There are two subtypes of ACH receptors: 

-Nicotinic, found in skeletal muscle (neuromuscular junction), autonomic ganglia, (sympathetic and parasympathetic), brain (Nicotine activates them) 

-Muscarinic, found in heart, glands, eyes, GI, lungs, etc. (Hallucinogenic Amanita muscaria produces muscarine compound which activates them) 

 

-Adrenergic refers to nerve cells and fibers which use NA as their neurotransmitter 

-Cholinergic refers to those which use ACH. 

 

Describe the relationship between the adrenergic/cholinergic systems and the sympathetic/parasympathetic systems. 

The sympathetic pathway uses ACH as the preganglionic neurotransmitter, and NA for postganglionic. (Except skin, skin blood vessels, sweat glands where the sympathetic fibers secrete ACH.) 

 

The parasympathetic pathway exclusively uses ACH.  

 

 

 

Identify the targets for adrenaline, noradrenaline, and acetylcholine in the synapses of the autonomic nervous system.  

 

There are two types of noradrenaline and adrenaline receptors: 

Alpha- blood vessels, GI, brain; are most responsive to NA, then adrenaline, then isoprenaline 

Beta- heart, lungs, kidney, brain; are most responsive to isoprenaline, then adrenaline, then NA 

 

There are 2 alpha receptor subtypes, each with 3 further sub-subtypes. 

There are 3 beta receptor subtypes.  

 

 

Muscarinic ACH receptors (5 subtypes, M1-5) 

These are members of the G protein-coupled receptor superfamily, and are used to activate/inhibit target effector eg enzymes and ion channels. These cause cellular effects on the timescale of seconds. 

 

They can activate phospholipase C to increase inositol triphosphate and diacylglycerol for cell excitation, at M1 (neurons), M3 (glands/smooth muscle eg bronchoconstriction of lungs), M5 (CNS, salivary glands).   

 

They can  inhibit adenylate cyclase to reduce cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) for cell inhibition, at M2 (cardiac) and M4 (CNS).  

 

Apart from signaling cascades, certain subtypes use additional signaling; M1 inhibits K+ conductance whilst M2 increases K+ conductance, and M3 increases Ca2+ conductance. 

 

Nicotinic ACH receptors  

These receptors are comprised of 5 subunits each.  

 

The ACH binding site is at the junction between an alpha subunit and its neighbour. Thus, 2 alpha subunits are required for 2x ACH binding per receptor. Nicotinic receptors operate ligand-gated ion channels. This allows very fast cellular effects, on the time scale of milliseconds.  

 

Briefly describe the function of the adrenal gland (medulla) as part of the sympathetic nervous system. 

 

Catecholamine biosynthesis occurs primarily in the chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla, as part of the sympathetic nervous system. Catecholamines are the group of compounds including noradrenaline, adrenaline and dopamine.  

 

Tyrosine is the amino acid precursor of adrenaline. The enzyme tyrosine hydroxylase converts this into DOPA, and this enzyme is the rate-limiting step. With further enzymes, DOPA is converted into Dopamine, then into Noradrenaline, then Adrenaline.
